1
00:00:01,000 --> 00:00:04,073
Subtitles downloaded from Podnapisi.NET

2
00:00:59,039 --> 00:01:06,512
In '78, I came to Europe for the first time
to compete outside Brazil in the World Championship

3
00:01:11,799 --> 00:01:14,313
It was pure driving, pure racing.

4
00:01:14,879 --> 00:01:17,599
There wasn't any politics.

5
00:01:18,000 --> 00:01:21,230
No money involved either.
It was real racing.

6
00:01:31,799 --> 00:01:35,597
We did not think that karting
could become a career.

7
00:01:35,679 --> 00:01:36,680
AYRTON'S FATHER
MILTON DA SILVA

8
00:01:36,799 --> 00:01:40,270
But it has become a
big part of our lives

9
00:01:40,479 --> 00:01:46,471
and we are a bit worried because
then along came Formula One.

10
00:01:47,319 --> 00:01:49,037
May God protect him forever.

11
00:01:49,237 --> 00:01:50,239
AYRTON'S MOTHER
NEYDE SENNA

12
00:01:50,240 --> 00:01:52,959
All the dangers are my biggest fear.

13
00:01:53,120 --> 00:01:56,031
I would like to thank him
because he is a good son

14
00:01:56,120 --> 00:02:00,954
and this year he has worked
very hard and honestly.

15
00:02:01,760 --> 00:02:04,194
For me, it is more important than any title.

16
00:02:10,560 --> 00:02:12,835
Few really do know myself

17
00:02:12,919 --> 00:02:17,913
They just don't understand what it takes
to be a racing driver.

18
00:02:18,400 --> 00:02:20,754
Somebody that has, left behind,

19
00:02:20,840 --> 00:02:23,513
thousands and thousands of miles away,
family and friends

20
00:02:23,599 --> 00:02:25,396
to live in Europe.

21
00:02:26,079 --> 00:02:29,469
Being so young.
I have always been fighting.

22
00:02:29,759 --> 00:02:31,431
Nothing ever has come easy.

23
00:02:36,560 --> 00:02:38,151
The time has come.

24
00:02:38,240 --> 00:02:42,074
Ayrton is ready to ride for the first time
a Formula One car.

25
00:02:43,639 --> 00:02:47,758
I believe it was God
to give me this opportunity,

26
00:02:47,960 --> 00:02:50,837
I've been waiting a long time.

27
00:02:51,120 --> 00:02:54,590
And now it is also helping
to remain calm, tranquil, relaxed.

28
00:03:09,560 --> 00:03:14,110
Well I always liked the combination of
the man and the machine

29
00:03:14,520 --> 00:03:19,195
I think that's the real special quality
that motor racing in general

30
00:03:19,280 --> 00:03:22,750
and, particular, particularly Formula One has

31
00:03:22,840 --> 00:03:25,069
And you know people say:
"Oh, It's all about the car, isn't it?"

32
00:03:25,159 --> 00:03:30,280
Well, actually it's not. But the car is
certainly, 50%, maybe even a little bit more

33
00:03:31,039 --> 00:03:34,715
Even if it's 75% or 80%,

34
00:03:34,800 --> 00:03:37,519
The other 20%, which is represented by the driver

35
00:03:37,599 --> 00:03:40,557
is absolutely crucial.
That can make the difference.

36
00:03:41,920 --> 00:03:46,117
But the cars themselves - you either believe this or you don't -

37
00:03:46,199 --> 00:03:48,953
The cars themselves are beautiful things.

38
00:03:49,560 --> 00:03:53,917
They are a little less beautiful when they are painted
like cigarette packets

39
00:03:54,000 --> 00:03:56,389
or whatever they paint them as now, perhaps,

40
00:03:56,479 --> 00:04:03,237
but there's a beauty to the
sense of form following function,

41
00:04:03,319 --> 00:04:06,437
that the form of the car
expresses in some way

42
00:04:06,520 --> 00:04:09,717
the speed that they are going
to go at when they start moving

43
00:04:09,800 --> 00:04:13,474
And the details of the engineering,

44
00:04:13,560 --> 00:04:18,997
even if you are not technically literate,
are very beautiful.

45
00:04:19,560 --> 00:04:22,518
They are beautiful bits of
sculptures, if you like.

46
00:04:22,879 --> 00:04:29,274
And that combination of the
beautiful, inanimate machines

47
00:04:29,920 --> 00:04:33,629
and the hero figures of the drivers

48
00:04:34,240 --> 00:04:40,951
the sense of courage and romance,
and that sort of thing

49
00:04:42,560 --> 00:04:47,156
is what attracted me, I think,
when I was a small boy.

50
00:04:47,920 --> 00:04:49,750
I think Formula One in the 80s was

51
00:04:49,840 --> 00:04:52,831
one of the most glorious times
in Formula One

52
00:04:53,519 --> 00:04:58,071
The cars were almost simple,
compared to what they are now.

53
00:04:58,159 --> 00:05:03,598
The steering wheel only turned the car.
The gear lever, shifted the gears.

54
00:05:03,680 --> 00:05:07,434
It was a time when drivers
still made the difference

55
00:05:07,519 --> 00:05:12,435
and all the engineering expertise
and all the eletronics

56
00:05:13,360 --> 00:05:15,749
still left a great deal for the driver to do.

57
00:05:16,720 --> 00:05:21,918
You had Alain Prost, known as "The Professor"

58
00:05:22,000 --> 00:05:26,151
A very smooth, calculating driver

59
00:05:26,240 --> 00:05:29,788
You had Nelson Piquet, who was Brazilian,

60
00:05:29,879 --> 00:05:36,034
very emotional, very clever, cunning driver.

61
00:05:36,800 --> 00:05:40,793
You had Nigel Mansell, who was sort of a British lion

62
00:05:40,879 --> 00:05:45,670
who was very exciting to watch,
very spectacular driver.

63
00:05:45,759 --> 00:05:49,069
And then you had Senna, the virtuoso.

64
00:05:49,920 --> 00:05:53,707
And to see these drivers competing
with each other

65
00:05:54,560 --> 00:05:57,949
At more or less the same stage
in their careers,

66
00:05:58,639 --> 00:06:01,312
overlapping slightly, in a way,

67
00:06:01,399 --> 00:06:05,995
but really at their peak together, was phenomenal.

68
00:06:08,160 --> 00:06:11,788


69
00:06:31,600 --> 00:06:33,670
Ayrton, this is a beautiful city,

70
00:06:33,759 --> 00:06:37,435
with wonderful streets to walk,
but unsuitable to host a race, no?

71
00:06:37,519 --> 00:06:38,555
REGINALDO LEME

72
00:06:39,240 --> 00:06:41,470
Indeed. I arrived at the last minute

73
00:06:41,680 --> 00:06:44,148
and I was surprised.
I've never been to Monaco.

74
00:06:44,480 --> 00:06:47,437
I did some testing

75
00:06:47,519 --> 00:06:51,512
and fortunately, I managed
to adapt to the track.

76
00:06:51,920 --> 00:06:56,356
There is no margin for error,
any error would result in an accident.

77
00:06:56,720 --> 00:06:58,358
But for now, I'm satisfied.

78
00:07:01,439 --> 00:07:04,670
I was travelling a lot, as a
Formula One journalist

79
00:07:04,759 --> 00:07:07,672
when Ayrton began to be noticed
driving a Toleman.

80
00:07:07,759 --> 00:07:08,749
VOICE OF REGINALDO LEME
GLOBO TV COMMENTATOR

81
00:07:10,839 --> 00:07:13,990
Toleman was not a winning team.

82
00:07:14,319 --> 00:07:20,069
The car was bad and never won a race.

83
00:07:20,399 --> 00:07:25,713
That's why what Ayrton did in Monaco
was true genius.

84
00:07:28,319 --> 00:07:32,233
Now, lots of drivers do that.
Join a small team,

85
00:07:32,680 --> 00:07:36,274
and disappear without a trace.
They perform to the level of the team.

86
00:07:37,879 --> 00:07:43,716
But there is sort of a rare breed of drivers,
of which Senna was absolutely one,

87
00:07:44,199 --> 00:07:45,951
who can go into a small team

88
00:07:46,040 --> 00:07:50,511
and perform so far above the perceived
level of the car

89
00:07:51,120 --> 00:07:54,475
That everybody turns around and thinks:
"How did he do that?"

90
00:07:54,560 --> 00:07:59,509
What he had done
was to make everybody, *everybody* in the paddock,

91
00:07:59,600 --> 00:08:03,990
aware of what he could do,
who he was and what his potential was.

92
00:08:04,079 --> 00:08:07,959
That he could take this car
which had nothing,

93
00:08:08,040 --> 00:08:10,314
and deliver a result like that,

94
00:08:10,399 --> 00:08:13,709
in the worst possible conditions
for a racing driveer.

95
00:08:14,839 --> 00:08:19,470
It is impossible to overestimate
how frightening it is

96
00:08:19,600 --> 00:08:21,908
to race in the rain, how difficult it is.

97
00:08:22,000 --> 00:08:24,036
Racing drivers can't see anything if it rains,

98
00:08:24,120 --> 00:08:27,509
especially if they are behind another car.

99
00:08:27,680 --> 00:08:30,672
The big tires they have now
throw up so much spray

100
00:08:30,759 --> 00:08:33,956
that it's like driving in thick, thick, thick fog.

101
00:08:34,440 --> 00:08:39,355
You know, like tring to drive on a motorway
in a thick fog,

102
00:08:39,440 --> 00:08:43,956
with 20 yards of visibility,
at racing speeds.

103
00:08:44,759 --> 00:08:48,639
And to be able to do that, you know,
really sorts out

104
00:08:48,720 --> 00:08:50,789
the great racing drivers from the pretty good ones.

105
00:08:55,879 --> 00:08:58,792
Alain Prost, now after a superb start,
has got away in the lead.

106
00:08:58,879 --> 00:09:00,000
Monaco Grand Prix
3 June 1984
Eighth race Senna in Formula One

107
00:09:01,000 --> 00:09:03,309
Nigel Mansell second,
the two Ferraris third and fourth.

108
00:09:03,399 --> 00:09:06,119
Niki Lauda is in fifth position.

109
00:09:06,200 --> 00:09:07,599
Sixth is Rosberg.

110
00:09:07,679 --> 00:09:11,115
Seventh is Manfred Winkelhock.
Eighth is Ayrton Senna.

111
00:09:13,840 --> 00:09:16,354
But Senna has come up through the field

112
00:09:16,440 --> 00:09:19,557
He started in thirteenth place
and is now seventh.

113
00:09:24,159 --> 00:09:26,832
Off goes Nigel Mansell!

114
00:09:28,879 --> 00:09:34,000
Ayrton Senna has now passed Keke Rosberg
and is in third place

115
00:09:38,039 --> 00:09:39,075
VOICE OF GALVÄ‚O BUENO
GLOBO TV COMMENTATOR

116
00:09:39,159 --> 00:09:42,356
And overtakes Niki Lauda!

117
00:09:42,480 --> 00:09:46,552
Ayrton Senna
takes second place!

118
00:09:46,799 --> 00:09:49,951
At the most dangerous part of the track!

119
00:09:56,799 --> 00:09:58,312
VOICE OF JAMES HUNT
1976 FORMULA ONE WORLD CHAMPION

120
00:09:58,399 --> 00:10:00,390
Well I think we are watching the arrival
of Ayrton Senna,

121
00:10:00,480 --> 00:10:01,832
a truly outstanding talent.

122
00:10:04,000 --> 00:10:06,548
He is catching Alain Prost
something like three seconds a lap

123
00:10:07,759 --> 00:10:10,068
And that is pretty staggering performance.

124
00:10:12,080 --> 00:10:15,515
Prost is waving his hand to the officals.
He wants to stop the race.

125
00:10:15,600 --> 00:10:17,113
But who can blame him?

126
00:10:17,320 --> 00:10:23,634
There is in fact, from a purist
and dispassionate point of view

127
00:10:23,759 --> 00:10:25,239
that there is no reason to stop the race.

128
00:10:27,240 --> 00:10:29,629
There is an official infront of me
with a red flag.

129
00:10:29,759 --> 00:10:31,557
They want to stop running.

130
00:10:32,840 --> 00:10:34,158
And the checkered flag is going out

131
00:10:34,360 --> 00:10:36,157
Incredible!

132
00:10:36,279 --> 00:10:40,067
And Prost is stopping!
and Senna crosses the line before he gets there!

133
00:10:40,919 --> 00:10:44,116
Ayrton raises his arms
and gesturing with enthusiasm!

134
00:10:44,440 --> 00:10:47,511
Celebrating as if he won the race!

135
00:10:47,799 --> 00:10:49,836
If we had continued for a few more laps,

136
00:10:50,440 --> 00:10:54,149
I am sure Ayrton would have passed him.

137
00:10:56,320 --> 00:10:58,275
I had a serious chance of winning.

138
00:10:58,559 --> 00:11:01,677
But until you cross the finishing line
in first position,

139
00:11:01,799 --> 00:11:02,994
it is impossible to make a prediction.

140
00:11:03,159 --> 00:11:06,674
Formula One is politics, money

141
00:11:07,120 --> 00:11:10,794
and while you are making your way through it,
you must deal with such things.

142
00:11:11,679 --> 00:11:14,797
You have Alain Prost, a world champion,

143
00:11:14,879 --> 00:11:17,552
out there, leading the Monaco Grand Prix,

144
00:11:17,639 --> 00:11:22,316
survivng all those wet corners, going by many wrecks,

145
00:11:22,399 --> 00:11:25,517
driving his heart out
for a victory at Monaco

146
00:11:25,600 --> 00:11:28,831
And here comes,
first year Formula One driver

147
00:11:28,919 --> 00:11:33,072
from some place in Brazil,
Ayrton Senna.

148
00:11:33,159 --> 00:11:36,072
Now, this was one of the wettest races
I've ever been in

149
00:11:36,159 --> 00:11:38,389
and it needed to be stopped.

150
00:11:38,480 --> 00:11:41,630
But what Senna could not get, was that,

151
00:11:42,919 --> 00:11:47,913
It was in a French area,
considered a French event

152
00:11:49,000 --> 00:11:53,994
with the FIA being housed in Paris

153
00:11:54,480 --> 00:11:56,596
and run by Frenchmen.

154
00:11:57,679 --> 00:12:02,514
To him, there had to be some reason
beside the rain,

155
00:12:02,840 --> 00:12:05,399
that was no problem to him,

156
00:12:06,480 --> 00:12:08,436
to where they took this victory away from him.

157
00:12:08,519 --> 00:12:10,475
He knew that in another three or four laps

158
00:12:10,559 --> 00:12:13,312
he would catch Prost,
find a way around him

159
00:12:13,399 --> 00:12:14,991
and he would be in the number one position.

160
00:12:19,240 --> 00:12:21,629
A tragic result for Senna. However,

161
00:12:21,759 --> 00:12:23,591
if he is not the
World Champion this year,

162
00:12:23,759 --> 00:12:28,595
He will undoubtedly be World Champion in the future,
if his career continues.

163
00:12:29,759 --> 00:12:32,797
Ayrton Senna
the new star of Formula One!

164
00:12:33,840 --> 00:12:36,307
Appearing for the first time
on the Formula One podium

165
00:12:36,600 --> 00:12:38,875
after a fantastic performance.

166
00:12:41,559 --> 00:12:42,674
What about next year?

167
00:12:42,759 --> 00:12:44,671
Are you going to stay with the Toleman team?

168
00:12:44,759 --> 00:12:46,636
-What are your plans now?
-I don't know.

169
00:12:46,720 --> 00:12:47,674
JOHN BISIGNANO

170
00:12:47,759 --> 00:12:51,673
I don't know. At the moment it's still no decisions.
And nothing clear.

171
00:12:51,799 --> 00:12:55,315
We have to wait more time to see what happens.

172
00:12:55,399 --> 00:12:59,187
You are not going to be satisfied
until you are in a winning position though are you?

173
00:12:59,279 --> 00:13:03,239
I belive if you are doing something, like competing,
like motor racing

174
00:13:03,320 --> 00:13:05,754
you have either do well,
or forget it.

175
00:13:06,399 --> 00:13:09,517
I remember in Detroit,
a couple of weeks later,

176
00:13:09,639 --> 00:13:13,871
it was already a buzz between the media

177
00:13:14,720 --> 00:13:18,029
managers and sponsors,
looking after him

178
00:13:18,120 --> 00:13:21,317
I remember Philip Morris making a deal,

179
00:13:21,399 --> 00:13:24,278
a personal contract with him after that.

180
00:13:26,279 --> 00:13:31,673
And we knew he would not stay at the Toleman
for the three years

181
00:13:31,759 --> 00:13:33,671
for the supposed length of his contract,

182
00:13:33,759 --> 00:13:37,149
because the Toleman team was not really improving

183
00:13:37,240 --> 00:13:42,029
and the potential of the team was not big enough
for a talent.

184
00:13:46,279 --> 00:13:49,794


185
00:14:00,000 --> 00:14:04,471
LOTUS

186
00:14:04,840 --> 00:14:08,309
Lotus was the perfect place for Ayrton to move to.

187
00:14:08,399 --> 00:14:09,389
VOICE OF JOHN BISIGNAGNO
ESPN COMMENTATOR

188
00:14:09,480 --> 00:14:14,110
It was a team that had won Championships,
and had won many Grand Prix

189
00:14:14,320 --> 00:14:18,711
and they worked very very hard
around Ayrton, to give his talent

190
00:14:18,799 --> 00:14:21,758
all the facilities that he needed to win.

191
00:14:25,840 --> 00:14:28,433
When I first come to
Formula One in '84,

192
00:14:29,360 --> 00:14:30,918
I was starting.

193
00:14:31,000 --> 00:14:34,275
I had so much to learn and to achieve.

194
00:14:34,360 --> 00:14:37,989
Anything, any good result
was a progress

195
00:14:38,320 --> 00:14:39,991
was a motivation.

196
00:14:40,399 --> 00:14:43,119
Then I changed
to a bigger team, to Lotus,

197
00:14:43,200 --> 00:14:46,033
and still went up, and up and up.

198
00:14:46,159 --> 00:14:47,798
I'm still doing it.

199
00:14:47,879 --> 00:14:52,749
So even when I have some problems,
I look always to the next race.

200
00:14:53,200 --> 00:14:58,399
Because maybe one race I have no chance,
but the next one or the next five, will be good

201
00:14:58,519 --> 00:15:00,350
against one bad one.

202
00:15:00,679 --> 00:15:04,753
So you got to try and make the numbers
bigger and bigger.

203
00:15:11,080 --> 00:15:13,196
Even as a child, he
always knew what he wanted

204
00:15:14,519 --> 00:15:17,192
and he always got it.

205
00:15:17,639 --> 00:15:18,868
AYRTON'S MOTHER
NEYDA SENNA

206
00:15:18,960 --> 00:15:22,191
For example, he always paid attention
in the classroom at school,

207
00:15:22,399 --> 00:15:24,833
so he didn't have to study at home

208
00:15:24,919 --> 00:15:28,707
and so he had more time
to play on his go-kart.

209
00:15:33,240 --> 00:15:37,232
There is no doubt, that Senna came
from a background of privilege.

210
00:15:37,320 --> 00:15:39,197
VOICE OF RICHARD WILLIAMS
SPORTS JOURNALIST, THE GUARDIAN

211
00:15:39,279 --> 00:15:41,952
His family was very comfortably off.

212
00:15:42,120 --> 00:15:46,432
Once they recognized
that his ambition was to be a racing driver,

213
00:15:46,919 --> 00:15:50,754
they had no problem backing his early
efforts in go-karts.

214
00:15:55,080 --> 00:16:00,677
But it would be a great mistake to think that he
was able to buy his way into Formula One.

215
00:16:01,080 --> 00:16:03,071
Senna himself realized

216
00:16:03,480 --> 00:16:07,758
that to make a serious, lasting impact on Formula One

217
00:16:07,960 --> 00:16:11,634
he had to fight his way into it
by virtue of his talent.

218
00:16:11,919 --> 00:16:16,197
PORTUGUESE GRAND PRIX - APRIL 21st 1985
AYRTON'S SECOND RACE WITH LOTUS

219
00:16:21,919 --> 00:16:23,990
Ayrton was exceptional when it rained.

220
00:16:24,080 --> 00:16:25,195
REGINALDO LEME
GLOBO TV COMMENTATOR

221
00:16:25,440 --> 00:16:30,433
When the conditions were bad
and the track became slippery

222
00:16:30,519 --> 00:16:31,918
he had a higher gear.

223
00:16:44,639 --> 00:16:46,870
The Estoril race was incredible.

224
00:16:47,720 --> 00:16:51,110
He lapped all his opponents except one.

225
00:16:55,120 --> 00:16:58,475
It is wonderful!
An extraordinary feeling.

226
00:16:59,480 --> 00:17:03,359
I am very happy because,
in my second year in Formula One,

227
00:17:03,679 --> 00:17:07,150
I managed to fulfill my first dream,
which was to win my first Grand Prix.

228
00:17:13,400 --> 00:17:15,230
It is a unique thing.

229
00:17:16,000 --> 00:17:17,273
It's like a drug.

230
00:17:17,359 --> 00:17:22,387
This is something so strong and intense.

231
00:17:23,400 --> 00:17:27,711
Once you experience it,
you keep searching for it all the time.

232
00:17:32,599 --> 00:17:36,512
It was raining really hard.
There was no competition, really.

233
00:17:36,599 --> 00:17:42,231
He would have won that race if it was run 100 times.

234
00:17:42,319 --> 00:17:46,232
It was an important race for
Brazil for many reasons,

235
00:17:46,319 --> 00:17:50,074
including the fact that on that day,

236
00:17:50,160 --> 00:17:56,471
the first elected Brazilian President,
Tancredo Neves, died.

237
00:17:56,559 --> 00:18:00,075
It was a very important
political moment for Brazil,

238
00:18:00,160 --> 00:18:02,594
because he was the first elected president

239
00:18:02,680 --> 00:18:05,672
after the end of the dictatorship.

240
00:18:05,759 --> 00:18:09,912
He was ill for a long time and died.

241
00:18:10,000 --> 00:18:14,914
There was a risk that Brazil
would suffer another blow

242
00:18:15,000 --> 00:18:17,991
or something like that, which nobody wanted.

243
00:18:18,079 --> 00:18:22,596
Senna's win was very important
in that sense,

244
00:18:22,680 --> 00:18:27,230
for the public and the Brazilian people
and for us there,

245
00:18:27,319 --> 00:18:31,950
and I'm sure he also realized this
later in the evening

246
00:18:32,039 --> 00:18:35,316
when we were at dinner. We went to dinner,

247
00:18:35,400 --> 00:18:39,358
but later that night after leaving the
restaurant he caught a plane to return to Brazil.

248
00:18:39,839 --> 00:18:42,194
I'm Mili Okada
from Japan TV

249
00:18:42,319 --> 00:18:47,677
Fuji TV. I am just a TV personality,
not a news reporter, so,

250
00:18:47,799 --> 00:18:50,233
I see! Let's make a picture together.

251
00:18:50,319 --> 00:18:51,308
MILI OKADA
FUJI TV

252
00:18:52,640 --> 00:18:56,837
I think many Japanese girls are fans of Mr. Senna.

253
00:18:57,039 --> 00:18:59,679
Now I am close to him
and I'm so nervous ...

254
00:19:00,519 --> 00:19:03,114
Come and see Japan.
and see you in Japan.

255
00:19:03,200 --> 00:19:05,474
-Thank you! A little kiss.
-Thanks.

256
00:19:05,559 --> 00:19:07,516
Bye bye! Another kiss.

257
00:19:07,880 --> 00:19:10,394
He was very complete.

258
00:19:10,480 --> 00:19:14,519
From tires to the engine,
to every single component of the car,

259
00:19:14,599 --> 00:19:16,157
He wanted to know everything.

260
00:19:16,240 --> 00:19:21,836
He wasa pushing ever mechanic and every
engineer to the very limit,

261
00:19:21,920 --> 00:19:26,391
to understand, first of all
and to improve the overall package

262
00:19:27,119 --> 00:19:32,797
And it took a lot of his energy,

263
00:19:33,920 --> 00:19:39,631
but he was concentrating as much on that aspect of the job
as driving itself.

264
00:19:39,720 --> 00:19:44,669
He was the first one maybe,
to stay at the circuit

265
00:19:44,759 --> 00:19:48,513
Until nine, ten o' clock
with the engineers and mechanics.

266
00:19:48,599 --> 00:19:53,276
Didn't want to go back to the hotel
or go play golf like Alain Prost and a few others.

267
00:20:04,839 --> 00:20:07,433
There's only one word to describe Ayrton's style:

268
00:20:07,599 --> 00:20:09,750
and that is, "Fast".

269
00:20:10,960 --> 00:20:15,953
He would take the car
beyond its designed capabilities.

270
00:20:16,279 --> 00:20:22,833
He would brake later, fly into these corners
where the car was just, over the edge.

271
00:20:22,960 --> 00:20:26,713
And somehow, he could dance a dance
with that car

272
00:20:27,359 --> 00:20:29,634
to where it stayed on the track.

273
00:20:34,000 --> 00:20:36,638
As I watched Ayrton's early career,

274
00:20:36,720 --> 00:20:37,835
Voice of Ron Dennis
Team manager McLaren

275
00:20:37,920 --> 00:20:40,673
what was very apparent was his pace and his dedication

276
00:20:40,880 --> 00:20:44,713
But, in the end, what you're looking for is an intellect

277
00:20:46,119 --> 00:20:49,112
And I thought, "This guy's got what it takes."

278
00:20:56,240 --> 00:20:59,516
But it pretty soon became apparent that

279
00:20:59,599 --> 00:21:01,875
Lotus wasn't going to be big enough for him

280
00:21:01,960 --> 00:21:06,556
Lotus was actually a team
just beginning its decline.

281
00:21:07,279 --> 00:21:08,998
I think when he was there, really,

282
00:21:09,119 --> 00:21:12,270
there was nothing he could do to stop it.

283
00:21:12,640 --> 00:21:14,436
Y'know, the driver doesn't design the car.

284
00:21:14,519 --> 00:21:20,277
And so he did what he had done before,
and what great drivers do,

285
00:21:20,359 --> 00:21:24,511
which was to move again,
to an even more competitive team.

286
00:21:24,599 --> 00:21:27,034
Such an important instinct for a driver, that.

287
00:21:27,119 --> 00:21:28,837
To know where to be.

288
00:21:28,920 --> 00:21:31,229
To know not who is competitive, this season.

289
00:21:31,319 --> 00:21:33,151
But who is going to be competitive next.

290
00:21:34,680 --> 00:21:41,430
At that time the strongest teams
were Williams and McLaren.

291
00:21:41,519 --> 00:21:43,589
McLaren was,

292
00:21:45,279 --> 00:21:48,715
I would say, a constructor
which had always reflected

293
00:21:49,000 --> 00:21:50,876
the same values as Ayrton.

294
00:21:50,960 --> 00:21:54,236
In that sense Ayrton and Ron Dennis
have much in common.

295
00:21:54,319 --> 00:21:57,835
They are both perfectionists...

296
00:21:57,960 --> 00:22:00,234
Let's put it like this. Both have

297
00:22:00,319 --> 00:22:06,155
the idea that nothing will go wrong
if something is well planned and executed

298
00:22:06,240 --> 00:22:09,630
and have always fought
by the same ideals.

299
00:22:09,720 --> 00:22:15,435
Ron comes from a background of hard work.

300
00:22:15,559 --> 00:22:17,630
He has struggled to get where he is now

301
00:22:17,720 --> 00:22:21,394
and has been successful in life.
They are both very close.

302
00:22:21,680 --> 00:22:27,788
At that time the trilogy "The best
team, best driver, best car"

303
00:22:27,880 --> 00:22:31,349
was led by Ron Dennis at McLaren.

304
00:22:35,599 --> 00:22:38,717
In the mid-80s,
McLaren was the team to beat.

305
00:22:38,799 --> 00:22:43,112
Ron Dennis was the best manager
Alain Prost was the best driver.

306
00:22:43,200 --> 00:22:46,556
ALAIN PROST
WORLD CHAMPION 1985, 1986

307
00:22:46,640 --> 00:22:49,915
We all called Prost "The Professor"
because he would do

308
00:22:50,000 --> 00:22:53,470
methodically whatever it took
to be ahead on points.

309
00:22:53,640 --> 00:22:55,471
If it meant coming fifth,

310
00:22:55,640 --> 00:22:58,676
He would hold the fifth place
and collect those points,

311
00:22:58,759 --> 00:23:02,833
rather than fighting for second,
third or first place finish.

312
00:23:03,960 --> 00:23:07,509
And, he certainly understood the politics of the sport

313
00:23:08,000 --> 00:23:11,390
and he played that game smarter than anyone.

314
00:23:16,240 --> 00:23:18,151
You're known as "The Professor" of motor racing

315
00:23:18,240 --> 00:23:19,275
SELINA SCOTT
WOGAN TALK SHOW, BBC

316
00:23:19,359 --> 00:23:21,589
because you plan everything out
and you know where you're going

317
00:23:21,680 --> 00:23:23,113
Is that actually true?

318
00:23:23,200 --> 00:23:26,953
I'm very realistic.
So I think when I'm competitive,

319
00:23:27,039 --> 00:23:31,157
I know I'm competitive
When I'm not, I know that I'm not.

320
00:23:31,279 --> 00:23:32,554
Why are there no women racing drivers?

321
00:23:32,680 --> 00:23:36,638
I do not know exactly why
women are not very competitive

322
00:23:36,720 --> 00:23:39,677
in motor racing,
especially in Formula One.

323
00:23:39,880 --> 00:23:43,190
But you know you're a beautiful woman.
and I know somebody at McLaren

324
00:23:43,319 --> 00:23:46,392
who likes you very much.
And I can arrange it.

325
00:23:47,319 --> 00:23:51,471
Alain, you know, if someone teaches me how to drive

326
00:23:51,559 --> 00:23:53,596
a car, a racing car
I may be able to give up this job

327
00:23:53,680 --> 00:23:56,830
There is nothing important
I could not teach you.

328
00:24:01,119 --> 00:24:03,509
Does your wife drive you home?

329
00:24:06,160 --> 00:24:11,188
The first time I really met him and tried to talk to him

330
00:24:11,279 --> 00:24:13,794
was in '84, when we had,

331
00:24:13,880 --> 00:24:19,272
in Germany, we had a Mercedes appearance

332
00:24:19,599 --> 00:24:25,516
and we had a small race in Nurburgring,
with the new Mercedes 190, I think

333
00:24:25,920 --> 00:24:32,349
We had the old, not old but some Formula One drivers,
old Formula One drivers

334
00:24:33,720 --> 00:24:36,916
And I remember Dennis Hulme
and some other driver.

335
00:24:37,000 --> 00:24:39,115
And we had this competition

336
00:24:39,200 --> 00:24:40,917
and some people from Mercedes

337
00:24:41,039 --> 00:24:45,078
asked me, if I could wait
Ayrton at the airport.

338
00:24:45,359 --> 00:24:49,557
We were having a 10, 15 minute time difference.

339
00:24:49,640 --> 00:24:53,951
and I had a car,
so I was waiting for him to bring him there.

340
00:24:54,039 --> 00:24:57,316
It was the first time that we talked together,

341
00:24:57,400 --> 00:25:02,029
and we had a long drive, something like
two or three hours

342
00:25:02,119 --> 00:25:05,270
So we had time to talk.
We didn't talk very much

343
00:25:05,359 --> 00:25:07,714
but he was... he looked impressed. He looked impressed

344
00:25:07,799 --> 00:25:11,269
because I was driving very fast
on the motorway in Germany.

345
00:25:11,359 --> 00:25:13,634
He said, "You're driving faster"

346
00:25:14,480 --> 00:25:17,756
It was nice,
and we were quite close,

347
00:25:17,839 --> 00:25:21,037
because he did not know anybody.

348
00:25:21,119 --> 00:25:25,954
So he was always close to me
during the first day.

349
00:25:26,039 --> 00:25:30,317
And it was funny, because

350
00:25:31,319 --> 00:25:34,436
he looked very open, very nice

351
00:25:34,519 --> 00:25:38,115
and then we were starting the practice

352
00:25:38,200 --> 00:25:41,351
and then we were fighting together for the pole position.

353
00:25:41,680 --> 00:25:45,558
And I saw him, very, you know, very competitive.

354
00:25:45,839 --> 00:25:50,355
I'm at the pole, he was second and then at the start

355
00:25:51,599 --> 00:25:57,072
He went before the flag
and I said to myself: "Shit."

356
00:25:57,480 --> 00:26:01,836
"I have to take care of this guy"

357
00:26:01,920 --> 00:26:02,909
That was in '84.

358
00:26:03,039 --> 00:26:06,952
I didn't know we'll be teammates or whatever.

359
00:26:07,440 --> 00:26:13,672
In Formula One your teammate
is your biggest rival,

360
00:26:13,799 --> 00:26:16,836
the first person to beat

361
00:26:16,960 --> 00:26:20,111
because he is the only one who
has a car equal to your own.

362
00:26:20,200 --> 00:26:23,749
I can have the excuse that I run in the
McLaren and the Ferrari is better

363
00:26:23,839 --> 00:26:27,115
or I can be in the Ferrari when the
McLaren is better, but I can't say

364
00:26:27,200 --> 00:26:32,269
that my Ferrari is different
from that of my teammate.

365
00:26:32,400 --> 00:26:36,633
Usually early in his career

366
00:26:36,720 --> 00:26:38,950
when a driver arrives in a team

367
00:26:39,039 --> 00:26:41,792
his main rival is his teammate.

368
00:26:41,880 --> 00:26:47,230
If he goes fatster than his
teammate has a chance to move on.

369
00:26:47,319 --> 00:26:49,913
If he doesn't accomplish this,
it's the end of his career.

370
00:26:50,440 --> 00:26:53,477
Prost had already won
two world championships there.

371
00:26:53,559 --> 00:26:55,152
He'd been there for several seasons,

372
00:26:55,240 --> 00:26:57,834
he was extremely well-established in the team.

373
00:26:57,920 --> 00:27:00,513
He thought of himself
and he thought he got the team to think of him

374
00:27:00,599 --> 00:27:03,067
as the number one driver in the team

375
00:27:03,160 --> 00:27:04,638
the team leader.

376
00:27:04,720 --> 00:27:08,998
The guy to whom most of their efforts were devoted.

377
00:27:09,920 --> 00:27:11,830
But then Senna joined

378
00:27:11,920 --> 00:27:16,835
and Senna was not going to accept a number two
status that's for sure

379
00:27:16,920 --> 00:27:20,070
He hadn't joined the team to be the supporting cast.

380
00:27:23,160 --> 00:27:26,788
ANNOUNCEMENT OF THE MCLAREN DRIVERS

381
00:27:27,319 --> 00:27:30,675
We are very confident that we have the best two drivers
in the world

382
00:27:30,759 --> 00:27:32,034
RON DENNIS
MCLAREN TEAM MANAGER

383
00:27:32,119 --> 00:27:35,112
And the two most professional drivers as well.

384
00:27:36,039 --> 00:27:40,954
And if we're not consistently in the winning circle next year,

385
00:27:41,480 --> 00:27:45,632
Then we certainly won't be able to put the blame on the drivers.

386
00:27:45,720 --> 00:27:48,711
It is a great opportunity for me,
professional,

387
00:27:48,839 --> 00:27:54,517
And on a personal point of view
I feel very happy to work together with Alain.

388
00:27:56,599 --> 00:28:02,310
The first year at McLaren was a very
decisive year in the life of Ayrton.

389
00:28:02,400 --> 00:28:03,388
VIVIANE SENNA
AYRTON'S SISTER

390
00:28:04,759 --> 00:28:06,511
He was very nervous.

391
00:28:07,079 --> 00:28:10,516
It was as if he bore the weight
of the world on his shoulders

392
00:28:11,079 --> 00:28:15,756
because they now had the responsibility

393
00:28:15,880 --> 00:28:20,237
to demonstrate he was
a first rate driver.

394
00:28:21,920 --> 00:28:23,955
Before Senna arrived at McLaren

395
00:28:24,039 --> 00:28:28,556
Alain Prost was considered the destroyer
of team-mates.

396
00:28:28,640 --> 00:28:33,159
I remember Jo Ramirez said to me:

397
00:28:33,240 --> 00:28:35,548
"Reginald, I am very concerned

398
00:28:35,640 --> 00:28:39,029
"What will happen
with Ayrton Senna at McLaren.

399
00:28:39,119 --> 00:28:44,950
"I know he has talent,
but Prost is a fighter,

400
00:28:45,039 --> 00:28:48,237
"He creates an atmosphere of war

401
00:28:48,319 --> 00:28:50,549
"Which helps him to destroy his opponents,

402
00:28:50,640 --> 00:28:53,711
"As he did with Keke Rosberg."

403
00:28:53,799 --> 00:28:57,155
Using the word "destroy"
in the technical sense.

404
00:28:57,240 --> 00:29:02,992
Destroyed on the track,
beating his opponent mentally.

405
00:29:03,079 --> 00:29:05,673
I said to Jo Ramirez:

406
00:29:05,759 --> 00:29:07,671
"Jo, with Senna it will be different.

407
00:29:07,759 --> 00:29:12,199
"Because he has more
talent than the other drivers

408
00:29:12,279 --> 00:29:15,077
"Prost will look to divide the team."

409
00:29:15,160 --> 00:29:17,070
And that's what happened.

410
00:29:17,160 --> 00:29:19,151
Alain Prost was scared..

411
00:29:19,240 --> 00:29:23,788
Despite all that Prost had
in terms of talent,

412
00:29:23,880 --> 00:29:26,791
understanding of race, intelligence

413
00:29:26,880 --> 00:29:29,916
and cold blood, he was surprised

414
00:29:30,000 --> 00:29:32,912
when he began racing with Ayrton.
He would never have thought

415
00:29:33,039 --> 00:29:35,554
a driver could be as good as Ayrton was.

416
00:29:49,960 --> 00:29:50,994


417
00:29:51,079 --> 00:29:54,197
Ayrton, for the first time in his career
has a car able of to be world champion

418
00:29:54,279 --> 00:29:58,955
and does not want to let
this chance going away.

419
00:29:59,240 --> 00:30:01,515
-This is normal and this will push on.
-What about you?

420
00:30:01,640 --> 00:30:04,107
-What about you?
-For me it's a little bit different.

421
00:30:04,279 --> 00:30:06,349
You mean you'll let it go?

422
00:30:06,480 --> 00:30:11,554
I have a little more pressure...
you put me more pressure.

423
00:30:13,319 --> 00:30:14,469
I think you could see

424
00:30:14,559 --> 00:30:15,628
VOICE OF RON DENNIS
MCLAREN TEAM MANAGER

425
00:30:15,720 --> 00:30:20,509
smiles, but at the same time,
some slightly strange body language

426
00:30:20,640 --> 00:30:24,917
as they realized just where they were
and what was going to unfold.

427
00:30:25,480 --> 00:30:30,473
Alain, who obviously, felt
he was well nested down at McLaren,

428
00:30:30,559 --> 00:30:35,155
And the young pretender coming in
and clearly threatening that position.

429
00:30:36,559 --> 00:30:40,711
Both had great intellect
and both were very good racing drivers.

430
00:30:40,839 --> 00:30:44,195
Beating each other, became far more challenging

431
00:30:44,359 --> 00:30:46,874
than beating the rest of the field.

432
00:30:49,279 --> 00:30:53,671
He had a target.
That is obvious that when he arrived in Formula One he had a target.

433
00:30:53,759 --> 00:30:56,068
And it was myself.

434
00:30:56,519 --> 00:30:59,432
When I arrived in Formula One,
I was happy to be there.

435
00:30:59,519 --> 00:31:03,194
We had different top drivers.
I've never had any target.

436
00:31:03,279 --> 00:31:08,307
Anybody driver that I
"I want to beat him!"

437
00:31:11,400 --> 00:31:14,631
I had huge respect for the
old drivers.

438
00:31:15,160 --> 00:31:18,674
For Ayrton it was different.
He really wanted to beat me.

439
00:31:18,759 --> 00:31:23,549
He really wanted to be World Champion
and beating me

440
00:31:23,640 --> 00:31:25,073
That was really his strength,

441
00:31:25,160 --> 00:31:29,914
that was a plus in his approach

442
00:31:30,000 --> 00:31:34,630
because when you are a racing driver
You want to have motivation.

443
00:31:37,519 --> 00:31:42,673
MONACO GRAND PRIX
14 May 1988

444
00:31:45,079 --> 00:31:51,348
1. A. SENNA
2. A. PROST
DIFFERENCE: 55.114 secs

445
00:31:52,319 --> 00:31:58,838
That day, I suddenly realized
I was no longer driving conscious.

446
00:32:00,559 --> 00:32:03,551
And I was in a different dimension for me.

447
00:32:04,279 --> 00:32:08,478
The circuit for me was a tunnel
Which I was just going. Going going

448
00:32:09,279 --> 00:32:14,035
And I realize I was way beyond my conscious understanding.

449
00:32:30,519 --> 00:32:35,833
Ayrton was multiple seconds into the lead.
He had the race in hand.

450
00:32:35,920 --> 00:32:36,909
67/78 LAPS

451
00:32:37,000 --> 00:32:42,313
With only a handful of laps to go
And he received a radio message that said

452
00:32:42,400 --> 00:32:45,311
"You are so far in the lead."
"Slow down."

453
00:32:48,680 --> 00:32:50,989
Ayrton Senna has hit the wall.

454
00:32:51,079 --> 00:32:53,752
Senna is in the barrier!
He's out of the car ...

455
00:32:53,839 --> 00:32:56,751
Ayrton Senna is out of his car
and out of this race.

456
00:32:56,839 --> 00:33:00,752
Ayrton Senna goes out of the lead of the
Monaco Grand Prix.

457
00:33:00,839 --> 00:33:03,637
Absolutely incredible!

458
00:33:03,720 --> 00:33:05,278
A. PROST
WINNER MONACO GP 1988

459
00:33:07,880 --> 00:33:10,598
He never wanted beat me.
He wanted to humiliate me.

460
00:33:10,680 --> 00:33:11,749
VOICE OF ALAIN PROST

461
00:33:11,880 --> 00:33:13,871
He wanted to show the people that
he was much stronger

462
00:33:13,960 --> 00:33:16,712
And much better.
And that was his weakness.

463
00:33:23,039 --> 00:33:28,478
His post-accident emotion
was pure anger with himself.

464
00:33:29,200 --> 00:33:31,952
And he couldn't cope with it. At all

465
00:33:32,039 --> 00:33:35,191
He actually walked back to his apartment

466
00:33:35,279 --> 00:33:38,589
and it was two or three hours before he surfaced.

467
00:33:46,839 --> 00:33:52,073
I just came so close to perfection that weekend
that I relaxed

468
00:33:52,599 --> 00:33:56,751
I opened windows for mistakes
And I learned that there

469
00:34:00,240 --> 00:34:03,516
Since then, I progressively
come back because I lost some confidence.

470
00:34:03,599 --> 00:34:06,636
Progressively I fight back

471
00:34:06,759 --> 00:34:10,230
and I got much stronger,
after that incident.

472
00:34:10,960 --> 00:34:17,432
Somehow, I got closer to God
and that was very important for me as a man.

473
00:34:24,039 --> 00:34:27,157
Monaco was the turning point in the '88 season

474
00:34:28,760 --> 00:34:31,193
Ayrton went on an amazing run,

475
00:34:31,280 --> 00:34:34,077
winning six of
the next eight races

476
00:34:34,159 --> 00:34:37,596
