00:44:52,639 --> 00:44:56,268


613
00:45:02,159 --> 00:45:03,228
VOICE OF RON DENNIS
MCLAREN TEAM MANAGER

614
00:45:03,320 --> 00:45:07,791
1989 season was somewhat less harmonious than the year before

615
00:45:08,760 --> 00:45:12,514
Both drivers took on different levels of aggression.

616
00:45:12,599 --> 00:45:13,715
1 Ayrton Senna
2 Alain Prost

617
00:45:13,800 --> 00:45:15,552
especially when racing each other.

618
00:45:17,199 --> 00:45:19,838
It is curious

619
00:45:19,920 --> 00:45:24,197
that the English term "teammate"
is translated into the Portuguese "companheiros de equipe".

620
00:45:24,280 --> 00:45:28,114
I've often used the term
"Enemies of the team".

621
00:45:28,199 --> 00:45:34,710
Because if you have two drivers, as
in the case Prost and Ayrton,

622
00:45:34,800 --> 00:45:41,713
as teammates, inevitably
internal strife will arise.

623
00:45:42,039 --> 00:45:44,713
As a journalist and as someone who was in

624
00:45:44,800 --> 00:45:47,552
a TV production meeting,
every weekend

625
00:45:47,679 --> 00:45:50,353
talking about what's the story,

626
00:45:50,440 --> 00:45:52,590
We loved the rivalry.

627
00:45:53,000 --> 00:45:58,233
We loved it on the track, in the garage and in the motorhome afterwards

628
00:45:58,480 --> 00:46:02,711
Ron was really behind Ayrton.

629
00:46:03,920 --> 00:46:07,117
But I understood that very quickly

630
00:46:10,000 --> 00:46:14,869
It's business.
For him it's business, and I always understood.

631
00:46:15,000 --> 00:46:17,467
When I was with Niki,

632
00:46:18,199 --> 00:46:21,032
It was, I would say half and half at the beginning

633
00:46:21,119 --> 00:46:24,271
and then he went, obviously, behind me,

634
00:46:24,360 --> 00:46:28,239
because I was
the new generation and Ayrton was,

635
00:46:28,320 --> 00:46:31,117
when I was with him,
the new generation.

636
00:46:31,760 --> 00:46:38,108
Throughout their period in McLaren,
they always had equality.

637
00:46:40,679 --> 00:46:45,309
We would go at some points, to quite extreme lengths

638
00:46:45,880 --> 00:46:49,509
Engine choice for example.
Once we have determined

639
00:46:50,320 --> 00:46:52,594
which two engines were going to be used in the race,

640
00:46:52,679 --> 00:46:57,309
then it would be, literally, sort of a number out of the hat routine.

641
00:46:57,400 --> 00:47:01,438
We put the two engine numbers
in some sort of container,

642
00:47:01,519 --> 00:47:04,159
then the drivers would alternate.

643
00:47:05,679 --> 00:47:07,954
This was, probably

644
00:47:09,320 --> 00:47:11,117
to eliminate the view

645
00:47:11,199 --> 00:47:13,873
that Honda was selecting which engines went to whom.

646
00:47:13,960 --> 00:47:15,108
But it was,

647
00:47:15,199 --> 00:47:19,112
a degree of paranoia, because it didn't needed much.

648
00:47:19,199 --> 00:47:23,795
A slightly better engine or slightly better set-up

649
00:47:23,880 --> 00:47:26,791
that would determine who won the race.

650
00:47:26,880 --> 00:47:28,358
and who became World Champion.

651
00:47:28,519 --> 00:47:32,876
When it was Prost versus Senna in the same team,

652
00:47:32,960 --> 00:47:36,110
you know, the romantics would certainly go with Senna.

653
00:47:36,199 --> 00:47:39,556
and the pragmatists would go with Prost.

654
00:47:40,559 --> 00:47:43,791
And Senna could be a bit cruel about it,

655
00:47:43,920 --> 00:47:45,956
but there was some truth that

656
00:47:46,039 --> 00:47:49,554
Prost was one of those that made excuses quite a lot,

657
00:47:51,119 --> 00:47:53,030
which he never liked to hear from racing drivers.

658
00:47:53,119 --> 00:47:56,317
He'd rather they just fessed up, y'know.

659
00:47:56,920 --> 00:47:59,480
"The car wasn't good enough,"
"I wasn't quick enough on the day"

660
00:48:00,639 --> 00:48:03,313
or "That's the way things goes sometimes,"

661
00:48:03,440 --> 00:48:05,157
Prost would tend to go into the minutiae

662
00:48:05,239 --> 00:48:08,994
why the car wasn't good enough
or things had worked against him or..

663
00:48:09,079 --> 00:48:11,036
You know,

664
00:48:11,119 --> 00:48:17,115
even though every element of the explanation
might have truth in it somehow,

665
00:48:17,199 --> 00:48:21,637
It's unattractive. You don't want to hear it, actually.

666
00:48:28,920 --> 00:48:30,751
That's when the gloves come off in the team.

667
00:48:30,840 --> 00:48:32,034
VOICE OF JOHN BISIGNANO
ESPN COMMENTATOR

668
00:48:32,119 --> 00:48:35,715
That's when engineers stopped
sharing information.

669
00:48:35,800 --> 00:48:39,030
That's when drivers start looking over their shoulders to see

670
00:48:39,119 --> 00:48:41,315
who's getting what from whom.

671
00:48:43,960 --> 00:48:47,190
And Ayrton, with his love of truth,

672
00:48:47,280 --> 00:48:51,114
wasn't as in tune as Alain Prost

673
00:48:51,239 --> 00:48:54,550
with adding another dimension:
the politics of sport.

674
00:48:54,719 --> 00:48:56,199
Senna and Prost. Prost and Senna.

675
00:48:56,280 --> 00:48:58,635
The order of the grid is always one or the other.

676
00:48:58,719 --> 00:48:59,947
It is a war between them.

677
00:49:00,079 --> 00:49:01,637
For the French driver Alain Prost,

678
00:49:01,719 --> 00:49:04,836
he believes his teammate is unfair to him.

679
00:49:04,960 --> 00:49:09,711
and these disagreements could
affect the rest of the season.

680
00:49:12,159 --> 00:49:15,789
Grand Prix after Grand Prix they were
more and more distant from each other.

681
00:49:15,880 --> 00:49:16,994
REGINALDO LEME
GLOBO TV COMMENTATOR

682
00:49:17,079 --> 00:49:18,876
Ayrton said:
"This Frenchman is tough.

683
00:49:19,239 --> 00:49:20,355
"He wants war."

684
00:49:22,239 --> 00:49:23,559
After a little more time,

685
00:49:23,920 --> 00:49:26,592
they became completely isolated
and they didn't speak anymore.

686
00:49:29,920 --> 00:49:34,072
JEAN-MARIE BALESTRE
FIA PRESIDENT

687
00:49:34,639 --> 00:49:38,632
Of course having French FIA president Jean-Marie Balestre

688
00:49:38,719 --> 00:49:39,869
VOICE OF PIERRE VAN VILET
TF1 COMMENTATOR

689
00:49:39,960 --> 00:49:42,679
at that time was all for Alain
because they were close

690
00:50:01,360 --> 00:50:04,112
I remember Jean-Marie Balestre was the man in charge

691
00:50:04,199 --> 00:50:06,952
when Senna was denied the chance
to win the Monaco Grand Prix

692
00:50:07,039 --> 00:50:10,635
in the Toleman,
when he was a novice in Formula One.

693
00:50:11,639 --> 00:50:16,110
Balestre was a very divisive figure. Very confrontational.

694
00:50:17,719 --> 00:50:21,554
Argumentative and autocratic. Very autocratic.

695
00:50:22,760 --> 00:50:29,199
And Balestre was still in charge
in the late 80s

696
00:50:29,280 --> 00:50:32,556
and right through to the beginning of the '90s,

697
00:50:32,639 --> 00:50:37,918
when Prost and Senna
had their famous collisions at Suzuka.

698
00:50:40,000 --> 00:50:44,311
And Balestre was the man who attempted to
sanction

699
00:50:44,400 --> 00:50:47,755
and suspend, or whatever, Senna,

700
00:50:47,840 --> 00:50:51,628
who felt that he was being discriminated against

701
00:50:52,760 --> 00:50:54,556
there probably was some justification.

702
00:50:54,719 --> 00:50:58,235
Mr. Balestre had the room
beside me, on the other side,

703
00:50:58,320 --> 00:51:02,996
I entered into the room and Balestre was there

704
00:51:03,119 --> 00:51:07,989
and he came in to my room and we had a talk.

705
00:51:08,519 --> 00:51:12,114
Don't forget that I

706
00:51:12,199 --> 00:51:17,320
I had a very intense collaboration with

